.\" Manpage for the Pipes Python rewrite
.\" SPDX-License-Identifier: MIT
.TH PIPES 6 "21 July 2026" "3.0.0" "Pipes manual"
.SH NAME
pipes \- animated terminal pipes screensaver
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B pipes
.RI [ OPTION ]...
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B pipes
renders randomly routed, colored pipes in a POSIX terminal.
It is an unofficial, independently maintained Python rewrite of the classic
.B pipes.sh
screensaver.
.PP
The runtime uses terminfo capabilities and buffered terminal output directly.
It starts no shell or helper process, performs no network access, and writes no
persistent runtime files.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BI "-p " NUMBER
Number of independent pipes. The value must be at least 1. Default: 1.
.TP
.BI "-t " TYPE
Select a built-in pipe type from 0 through 9. May be repeated.
.TP
.BI "-t c" GLYPHS
Define a custom type using exactly 16 printable, non-combining, single-cell
Unicode codepoints. May be repeated.
.TP
.BI "-c " INDEX
Select a decimal terminfo foreground-color index. May be repeated.
.TP
.BI "-c #" HEX
Select a hexadecimal terminfo foreground-color index. May be repeated.
.TP
.BI "-f " FPS
Frame rate from 20 through 100. Default: 75.
.TP
.BI "-s " DENOMINATOR
Straight-movement probability denominator from 5 through 15. Default: 13.
.TP
.BI "-r " LIMIT
Clear the screen after exactly LIMIT drawn glyphs. Zero disables automatic
clearing. Default: 2000.
.TP
.B -R
Randomize starting position and direction.
.TP
.B -B
Disable bold rendering at startup.
.TP
.B -C
Disable color rendering at startup.
.TP
.B -K
Keep each pipe's type and color when crossing terminal edges.
.TP
.BR -h , " --help"
Show help and exit.
.TP
.BR -v , " --version"
Show version and exit.
.TP
.B --self-test
Run deterministic, non-interactive integrity checks and exit.
.TP
.BI "--seed " INTEGER
Use a deterministic random seed.
.SH KEYBOARD CONTROLS
.TP
.B P / O
Increase or decrease the straight-movement denominator.
.TP
.B F / D
Increase or decrease the frame rate.
.TP
.B B
Toggle bold immediately.
.TP
.B C
Toggle color immediately.
.TP
.B K
Toggle type/color retention at screen edges.
.PP
Any other key exits normally.
.SH PIPE TYPES
The ten built-in styles are heavy box, light arc, light square, double box,
ASCII plus, ASCII slash, dots, dot/O, railway, and knobby box drawing.
.PP
Each type contains 16 transition glyphs indexed by
.BR "old_direction * 4 + new_direction" .
Directions are up, right, down, and left. Reverse turns are never generated.
.SH COLORS
Color indices are passed to the terminal's
.B setaf
terminfo capability. When terminfo reports no usable color capability,
animation continues without color. Requested indices outside a positive
terminal color limit are rejected before terminal state is changed.
.SH TERMINAL BEHAVIOR
Interactive mode requires a TTY, a usable
.B TERM
value, and a terminfo database. Help, version, and self-test do not require a
TTY.
.PP
Normal exit, handled signals, and runtime errors restore saved terminal
attributes, cursor visibility, alternate-screen state, and signal handlers.
.SH FILES
.TP
.I pipes_sh.py
Single-file Python runtime and importable module.
.TP
.I LICENSE
Historical MIT license and copyright notices.
.SH EXIT STATUS
Zero indicates normal completion. Command-line or runtime errors return a
non-zero status. Handled INT, TERM, and HUP signals return 128 plus the signal
number after cleanup.
.SH HISTORY
Matthew Simpson created the original pipes program in 2010. Yu-Jie Lin later
developed it, and the Pipeseroni collective maintained the Bash project after
the MIT license was added.
.PP
This repository contains an unofficial Python rewrite independently maintained
by xnixjoyer. It is not an official Pipeseroni release.
